The paper deals with the topic of Quantitative Information Flow (QIF), which is a subfield of computer security and privacy. The use of game theory to model the interaction between the defender and the adversary in QIF suggests that the paper could belong to the cs.CR (Cryptography and Security) sub-category. The paper also deals with protocol composition, which is a topic in the cs.LO (Logic in Computer Science) sub-category. The use of probabilistic choice and the study of algebraic properties suggest that the paper could also belong to the cs.IT (Information Theory) sub-category. The use of game theory to model the interaction between the defender and the adversary also suggests that the paper could belong to the cs.GT (Computer Science and Game Theory) sub-category. Finally, the use of a formal framework to study the interaction between the defender and the adversary suggests that the paper could also belong to the cs.SY (Systems and Control) sub-category.
